div.div:
Another way to analyze lies/arguments is to:
- graph the system
- identify all positive priority directions, positive positions, positive intents possible in the system
- identify the limits of each path type (earning vs. lying) such as metrics used to make path selections
- assume that a liar will claim to be moving in a positive direction, moving with positive intents, using positive methods, and between positive positions
- if they can't move with positive positions/intents, they'll claim neutral positions/intents ('I didnt know', 'I thought someone else was doing it', etc), but they'll try to align their actions with positive positions/intents as much as possible, while minimizing work to support positive positions/intents
- they'll try to operate in intent space rather than position space bc intents are more difficult to measure
Then you can identify which paths are likely to be used for earning/lying intents:
- there will be clear paths used by people with positive intentions, that don't involve accepting rewards they didn't earn - these paths are easier to map than lying paths because the relationship between work & rewards is direct, explicitly stated, matches their actions with little room for error, & more calculatable most of the time than indirect rewards that a liar may be working towards with hidden intents or strategies.
- the honest earning path will have deviations that follow patterns of normal human error, and the lying path will have deviations that occasionally (or when being monitored or when planning to allow future excuses/ambiguity) overlap or align with the earning path
- the earning path will be clearly derivable from positive actions that can generate positive rewards, will be more independent because it requires developing/learning functionality, and when pressure is applied, the earning path will address the force being applied and use neutral/negative paths if necessary up to a point, but return to the earning path as soon as possible
- the earning path has clear limits on neutral/negative path usage potential, and the lying path has clear limits on work
- the earning path may generate the same points made as the lying path incentivizes, but there will be reasons why the earning path has those points ("I didnt know" is a response that can be used by earners if their earning activities/intents don't require them to know that - "I didnt know there was a strategy to do some other task" - as opposed to not knowing info they definitely knew that would have justified earning behavior over lying behavior)
- the earning path will have positive effects for other agents who are also on earning paths, whereas lying paths will usually generate positive effects for themselves or the ability to lie, which indirectly protects other liars
